# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/12th-united-states-congress] The **12th United States Congress** was a meeting of the legislative branch of the United States federal government, consisting of the United States Senate and the United States House of Representatives.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/12th-united-states-congress] It met in Washington, D.C. from March 4, 1811, to March 4, 1813, during the third and fourth years of James Madison's presidency.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/12th-united-states-congress] The apportionment of seats in the House of Representatives was based on the 1800 United States census.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/12th-united-states-congress] Both chambers had a Democratic-Republican majority.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/12th-united-states-congress] The count below identifies party affiliations at the beginning of the first session of this congress.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/12th-united-states-congress] Changes resulting from subsequent replacements are shown below in the "Changes in membership" section.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/12th-united-states-congress] During this congress, two new Senate seats were added for the new state of Louisiana.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/12th-united-states-congress] During this congress, one new House seat was added for the new state of Louisiana.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/12th-united-states-congress] This list is arranged by chamber, then by state.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/12th-united-states-congress] Senators are listed by class, and representatives are listed by district.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/12th-united-states-congress] Senators were elected by the state legislatures every two years, with one-third beginning new six-year terms with each Congress.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/12th-united-states-congress] Preceding the names in the list below are Senate class numbers, which indicate the cycle of their election.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/12th-united-states-congress] The names of representatives are preceded by their district numbers.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/12th-united-states-congress] The count below reflects changes from the beginning of the first session of this Congress.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/12th-united-states-congress] Lists of committees and their party leaders.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/13th-united-states-congress] The **13th United States Congress** was a meeting of the legislative branch of the United States federal government, consisting of the United States Senate and the United States House of Representatives.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/13th-united-states-congress] It met in Washington, D.C. from March 4, 1813, to March 4, 1815, during the fifth and sixth years of James Madison's presidency.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/13th-united-states-congress] The apportionment of seats in the House of Representatives was based on the 1810 United States census.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/13th-united-states-congress] The first two sessions were held at the Capitol building while the third, convened after the Burning of Washington, took place in the First Patent Building.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/13th-united-states-congress] Following the 1810 census, the size of the House was increased to 182 seats from 142.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/13th-united-states-congress] In this Congress, Class 1 meant their term ended with this Congress, requiring reelection in 1814; Class 2 meant their term began in the last Congress, requiring reelection in 1816; and Class 3 meant their term began in this Congress, requiring reelection in 1818.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The **1788–89 United States House of Representatives elections** were the first U.S.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] House of Representatives elections following the adoption of the Constitution of the United States.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Each state set its own date for its congressional elections, ranging from November 24, 1788, to March 5, 1789, before or after the first session of the 1st United States Congress convened on March 4, 1789.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] They coincided with the election of George Washington as the first president of the United States.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] With the new form of government needing to be operational prior to the completion of the first national census, Article I, Section 2, Clause 3 of the U.S.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Constitution set a temporary apportionment of seats.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Among the original 13 states, 11 of them ratified the Constitution and elected 59 total representatives.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] North Carolina and Rhode Island did not ratify the Constitution until after the 1st Congress began, and consequently did not elect their representatives until 1790.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Actual political parties did not yet exist, but new members of Congress were informally categorized as either "pro-Administration" (i.e., pro-Washington and pro-Hamilton) or "anti-Administration".
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The first session of the first House of Representatives came to order in Federal Hall, New York City on March 4, 1789, with only thirteen members present.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The requisite quorum (thirty members out of fifty-nine) was not present until April 1, 1789.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The first order of business was the election of a Speaker of the House.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] On the first ballot, Frederick Muhlenberg was elected Speaker by a majority of votes.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The business of the first session was largely devoted to legislative procedure rather than policy.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Article I, Section 2, Clause 3 of the U.S.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Constitution set a temporary congressional apportionment until the first national census was completed in 1790.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In the 18th and much of the 19th century, each state set its own date for elections.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In many years, elections were even held after the legal start of the Congress, although typically before the start of the first session.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In the elections for the 1st Congress, five states held elections in 1788, electing a total of 29 Representatives, and six held elections in 1789, electing a total of 30 Representatives.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Six seats were filled late because North Carolina and Rhode Island ratified the Constitution late.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] One pro-Administration representative resigned and the seat remained open at the end of the Congress.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] This was the first special election to the United States House of Representatives.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Under the law at the time, each voter cast two votes for representative, at least one of whom had to be from a different county.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Georgia had a mixed at-large/district system for the 1st Congress.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Representatives were elected at-large, but for three district-based seats.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Maryland had a mixed district/at-large system similar to Georgia's.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Massachusetts required a majority vote, necessitating additional votes if no one won a majority.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] This was necessary in 4 of the districts.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] — **The Documentary History of the First Federal Elections: 1788-1790*.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] New Hampshire law required a winning candidate to receive votes from a majority of voters (16.7% of votes).
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] No candidate won such a majority on the first ballot, so a second ballot was held February 2, 1789.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The election of all four representatives was contested, but the records that explained the precise grounds on which the election was contested have been lost due to the burning of Washington in the War of 1812.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] It is known to have related to questions of regularity and procedure.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] All four representatives' elections were ruled valid.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] New York held elections to the 1st Congress on March 3 and 4, 1789.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] They are retroactively numbered in this section.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] North Carolina ratified the Constitution late and thus elected representatives to the 1st Congress in 1790.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Pennsylvania held elections to the 1st Congress on November 26, 1788.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] For this first election (and again in 1792 election for the 3rd Congress), Pennsylvania chose to elect all of its representatives on a single statewide general ticket, an attempt by the pro-Administration-majority legislature to prevent anti-Administration candidates from winning seats.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Rhode Island ratified the Constitution late and thus elected representatives to the 1st Congress in 1790.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york] The **1789 United States House of Representatives elections in New York** were held on March 3 and 4, 1789, to elect 6 U.S.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york] Representatives to represent the State of New York in the 1st United States Congress.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york] The United States Constitution was adopted on September 17, 1787, by the Constitutional Convention in Philadelphia, and then ratified by the States.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york] On July 8, 1788, the Congress of the Confederation passed a resolution calling the first session of the 1st United States Congress for March 4, 1789, to convene at New York City and the election of U.S.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york] Representatives in the meanwhile by the States.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york] Constitution on July 26, 1788, by a very slim margin.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york] On January 27, 1789, the New York State Legislature divided the State of New York into six congressional districts which were not numbered.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york] Three Federalists and three Anti-Federalists (later known as the Democratic-Republicans) were elected.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york] Note: This was the first time political parties appeared in the United States.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york] Before the question of establishing a federal government, or not, arose, all candidatures had been personal.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york] Now, politicians aligned in two opposing groups: First those in favor of the establishment of a federal government and those against it, and then - after the federal government had been indeed established - those who supported it and those who did not.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york] The 1st United States Congress had convened at Federal Hall in New York City on March 4, 1789, without any members from the State of New York, and without a quorum in either Senate or House.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york] The first day with a quorum in the House was April 1.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york] The representatives elected in and near New York City took their seats soon after the election.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york] The upstate representatives needed some time to arrive, and Peter Silvester took his seat on April 22, John Hathorn on April 23, and Jeremiah Van Rensselaer on May 9.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-new-york] In April 1790, all six representatives ran for re-election: Floyd, Hathorn and Van Rensselaer (all Dem.-Rep.) were defeated; Laurance, Benson and Silvester (all Fed.) were re-elected.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The **1790–91 United States House of Representatives elections** were held on various dates in various states between April 27, 1790, and October 11, 1791.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Each state set its own date for its elections to the House of Representatives before or after the first session of the 2nd United States Congress convened on October 24, 1791.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] This was the first midterm election cycle, which took place in the middle of President George Washington's first term.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The size of the House increased to 67 seats after the new state of Vermont elected its first representatives.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] While formal political parties still did not exist, coalitions of pro-Washington (Pro-Admin.) representatives and anti-Administration representatives each gained two seats as a result of the addition of new states to the union.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Speaker Frederick Muhlenberg was succeeded by Jonathan Trumbull Jr., who became the 2nd Speaker of the House.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Either five or six incumbents did not seek re-election.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Aedanus Burke, a U.S. representative from South Carolina's 2nd congressional district, either retired or lost re-election but it is not known.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Pennsylvania at-large: Henry Wynkoop retired.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Pennsylvania at-large: Thomas Scott retired.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In this period, each state fixed its own date for congressional general elections, as early as April 27, 1790 (in New York) and as late as October 11, 1791 (in Pennsylvania).
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Elections to a Congress took place both in the even-numbered year before and in the odd-numbered year when the Congress convened.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In some states, the congressional delegation was not elected until after the legal start of the Congress (on the 4th day of March in the odd-numbered year).
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The first session of this Congress was convened in Philadelphia on October 24, 1791.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Kentucky and Vermont became states during the 2nd Congress, adding two seats each.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The legislation admitted Vermont was passed at the end of the 1st Congress taking effect on March 4, 1791, the first day of the 2nd Congress, so that Vermont was represented from the start of the Congress, while Kentucky was unrepresented until the 2nd session.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] There were special elections in 1790 and 1791 during the 1st United States Congress and 2nd United States Congress.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] New states and newly ratified states are not included as special elections.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Elections are sorted by date then district.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Connecticut elected all five of its representatives at-large on a general ticket on September 20, 1790.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] There were two subsequent special elections.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The first was held to fill the vacancy left by Pierpont Edwards (Pro-Admin.) declining to serve and was won by Jeremiah Wadsworth (Pro-Admin.).
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The second was held September 19, 1791, to fill the vacancy left by Roger Sherman (Pro-Admin.)'s election to the Senate and was won by Amasa Learned (Pro-Admin.).
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Georgia switched to a conventional district system for the Second Congress.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] At the time, the districts were not numbered, but are retroactively renumbered as the 1st, 2nd, and 3rd respectively here.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Kentucky was admitted during the 2nd Congress and elected its first representatives in 1792.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In Maryland, two local factions briefly emerged, the Chesapeake and Potomac (or Potowmack) "parties".
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The Potomac faction, consisting of individuals from the small counties of southern Maryland and the Eastern Shore, aimed to maintain their status by curbing the increasing influence of the city of Baltimore and the more populous counties.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] To do so, they supported the development of the federal city and a canal on the Potomac River to secure their economic future.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Conversely, the Chesapeake faction advocated for Baltimore's growth.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Their strategy involved improving the Susquehanna River to channel the lucrative wheat trade from western Maryland and Pennsylvania through Baltimore.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] They also believed that political representation should reflect population growth patterns rather than be defined by the counties.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] They feared that a canal on the Potomac River would undermine Baltimore's prosperity by diverting trade to competitors like Georgetown, the proposed federal city, and Alexandria.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Temporarily setting aside differences at the national level, the "Chesapeake Ticket" was formed to punish incumbents who had supported the Potomac location for the proposed federal city.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] A "Potomac Ticket" was organized and led by Governor Smallwood.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Turnout in Baltimore was around 99%, and almost every ballot was cast for the Chesapeake Ticket.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Statewide, the ticket won an overwhelming majority, securing all six seats.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] This victory threatened the county-based rural oligarchy, prompting the House of Delegates to transition from a mixed system to a district-based system on December 19, 1790.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Under this new system, all of Baltimore's votes would go to just one representative, Harford County was grouped with Kent and Cecil Counties, and Anne Arundel County was grouped with Prince George's County and Annapolis.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] With the base of the Chesapeake "party" split between three districts, the Chesapeake faction would disappear.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Massachusetts law required a majority for election.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] This condition was met in four of the eight districts, the remaining four required between 2 and 9 ballots for election.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] New York's districts were not numbered at the time, therefore the numbering here is retroactive.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] North Carolina ratified the Constitution November 21, 1789, and elected its representatives after admission.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Due to the cession of North Carolina's trans-Appalachian territory to form the Southwest Territory, the territory of the old 5th district was lost.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] North Carolina retained the same number of Representatives, and so it redistricted for the Second Congress.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Pennsylvania had elected its Representatives at-large in the 1st Congress, but switched to using districts in the 2nd Congress.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Five incumbents ran for re-election, four of whom won, while three others retired leaving three open seats.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Two districts had no incumbents residing in them, while one (the 8th district) had a single representative who declined to run for re-election and one (the 2nd district) had three incumbents, only one of whom ran for re-election.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Rhode Island ratified the Constitution May 29, 1790.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] It elected its representatives after admission.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Rhode Island held elections for the 2nd Congress on October 18, 1790, about six weeks after elections for the 1st Congress due to the state's late ratification of the Constitution.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Vermont was admitted at the end of the First Congress, with the admission taking effect at the start of the Second Congress.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Vermont was entitled to elect two representatives.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Vermont law at the time required a majority to win an office.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In the 1st district, no candidate won a majority, necessitating a run-off.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] The **1812–13 United States House of Representatives elections** were held on various dates in various states between August 3, 1812, and April 30, 1813.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Each state set its own date for its elections to the House of Representatives before the first session of the 13th United States Congress convened on May 24, 1813.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] They coincided with James Madison being re-elected president.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] With the addition of the new state of Louisiana's at-large seat, along with the 39-seat gain as a result of the congressional reapportionment based on the 1810 United States census, the size of the House increased to 182 seats.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Most relative population growth was in the West.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] After America's entry into the War of 1812 against Britain, the Democratic-Republican and Federalist parties maintained pro-war and anti-war positions, respectively.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Democratic-Republican representatives supported by voters in agrarian regions and Southern and Western states promoted war, asserting that Britain had violated American sovereignty and that despite Britain's strength, war was a manageable risk.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Federalists and their supporters in New England and more densely populated Eastern districts opposed the war, citing likely damage to American trade and infrastructure.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] This election saw significant voter support shift to the declining Federalists for the last time, almost entirely in New England, New York, and New Jersey.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Despite this shift, Federalists did not approach national political recovery, House control, or meaningful policy influence.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Following the 1810 census, the House was reapportioned, adding 39 new seats.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] There were special elections in 1812 and 1813 to the 12th United States Congress and 13th United States Congress.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Special elections are sorted by date then district.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Connecticut elected its members September 21, 1812.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Its apportionment was unchanged after the 1810 census.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Delaware gained a seat after the 1810 census, and chose to elect both seats on a general ticket.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] The ten years between 1813 and 1823 were the only time when Delaware was represented by more than one Representative, and is one of only three states (the other two being Alaska and Wyoming) that have never been divided into districts.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Delaware elected its members October 6, 1812.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Georgia gained two seats after the 1810 census.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Georgia elected its members October 5, 1812.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Kentucky gained four seats after the 1810 census.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Georgia elected its members August 3, 1812.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Louisiana held its election for the 13th Congress September 28–30, 1812, at the same time as the election for the 12th Congress, with nearly-identical results.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] It elected its members October 12, 1812.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Massachusetts gained three seats after the 1810 census, all of which were added to the District of Maine.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Its elections were held November 5, 1812, but since Massachusetts law required a majority for election, which was not met in the 19th district, a second ballot was held there January 6, 1813.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] New Hampshire gained one seat after the 1810 census.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Its elections were held August 31, 1812.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] New Jersey kept its delegation at six seats but changed from electing its Representatives on a statewide general ticket to using three plural districts of two seats each.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] These districts were used only for the 1812 election, and the state returned to using a single at-large district in 1814.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] This was only the second time that New Jersey used districts (the first being in 1798).
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] *Tufts Digital Collations and Archives*.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] A New Nation Votes: American Election Returns 1787–1825.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Archived from the original on August 7, 2020.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Ten seats were added after the 1810 census, bringing New York's representation to 27, the largest of any state at the time.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] New York would remain the state with the most members until surpassed by California in the 1970 census.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] There were two separate House of Representatives elections in 1812.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] The first was held in April 1812 for an un-reapportioned 17 representatives.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] This election was subsequently declared void and a new election was held on December 15–17, 1812, in which only three incumbents ran and two of whom were re-elected.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] New York thereby lost 4 Democratic-Republicans and gained 14 Federalists.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] North Carolina gained one representative as a result of the census of 1810.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Its elections were held April 30, 1813, after the term began but before Congress's first meeting.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] The 1810 census revealed dramatic population growth in Ohio since 1800, resulting in its representation increasing from a single Representative to six, resulting in the State being broken up into 6 districts, abolishing the at-large district.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Jeremiah Morrow (Democratic-Republican), who had served since Ohio achieved statehood in 1803, retired to run for U.S.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Senator, so that all six seats were open.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Its elections were held October 13, 1812.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] There was a special election in the 6th district, held due to the death of Representative-elect John S.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Pennsylvania gained five seats in the House of Representatives as a result of the census of 1810, which awarded it a total of 23 seats.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Pennsylvania was re-districted into 15 districts, one with 4 seats, five with 2, and the remaining nine with 1 seat each.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] There were seven open seats for this election, five resulting from the increase in apportionment, and two resulting from the retirement of incumbents.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p02] Rhode Island's apportionment was unchanged.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p02] Its elections were held August 25, 1812.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p02] South Carolina gained one representative as a result of the 1810 census, increasing from 8 seats to 9.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p02] Its elections were held October 12–13, 1812.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p02] Tennessee's representation increased from 3 seats to 6 as a result of the 1810 census.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p02] Its elections were held April 1–2, 1813, after the term began but before Congress's first meeting.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p02] Vermont gained two seats after the 1810 census.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p02] Rather than re-district, however, Vermont replaced its districts with a single at-large district.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p02] It would continue to use an at-large district in 1814, 1816, and 1818, then one more time in 1822 (with 5 seats).
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p02] Its elections were held September 1, 1812.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p02] Virginia gained one seat after the 1810 census, bringing its representation in the House of Representatives to 23 seats, the largest number Virginia would ever have.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p02] Virginia went from having the most representatives to having the second-most tied with Pennsylvania.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p02] New York, with its 27 seats, surpassed Virginia and remained the most populous state until the late 1960s.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p02] Its elections were held in April 1813, after the term began but before Congress's first meeting.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p02] Four territories had delegates in the 13th Congress: Illinois, Indiana, Mississippi, and Missouri.
[src:1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1812-13-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p02] Illinois Territory and Missouri Territory elected their delegates in 1812 for both the end of the 12th and the start of the 13th Congresses.
